  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model — the gold standard of intrinsic valuation. No multiples, no comparables, no vibes. Just future cash flows discounted to today.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with a Baseline Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>Mining companies like Freeport-McMoRan are incredibly capital-intensive. Free cash flow can swing wildly depending on the CapEx cycle (e.g., mine development). For this model, we start with the most recent actual Free Cash Flow of <strong>${fcfBase !== null ? fcfBase.toLocaleString() : 'N/A'} million</strong>. We acknowledge that Operating Cash Flow (${ocfBase !== null ? ocfBase.toLocaleString() : 'N/A'} million) provides a smoother baseline before CapEx, but ultimately, FCF is the true cash return to shareholders.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We grow FCF at <strong>8% per year</strong> for 5 years. This reflects the secular demand tailwinds for copper (EVs, renewable energy infrastructure, grid modernization) offset by the difficulty and high cost of expanding mine supply.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume FCF grows at <strong>2.5% forever</strong>. This is roughly aligned with long-term inflation and global GDP growth, acknowledging that while copper is essential, FCX operates in a cyclical, mature commodity market.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>All future cash flows are discounted at <strong>11%</strong>. This required rate of return reflects the 10Y Treasury (4.18%) plus a higher equity risk premium to account for geopolitical risks in mining jurisdictions (e.g., Indonesia, South America) and commodity price volatility.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Add net cash, divide by shares</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value + Net Cash (${netCash.toLocaleString()}M) = Equity Value. Divide by shares outstanding ({sharesOutstanding.toLocaleString()}M) for the per-share intrinsic value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>A DCF is only as good as its inputs. We're making exactly <strong>three</strong> judgment calls — everything else is math. Here's what we chose and why.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">8%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        The structural deficit in global copper supply supports higher sustained prices. While production growth is hard-fought, higher average realized prices and operational efficiencies should allow FCF to expand decently in the medium term, averaging 8%.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">11%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        10Y Treasury: 4.18%. Mining stocks carry inherent jurisdictional, environmental, and cyclical risks. A WACC of 11% acts as a necessary margin of safety for these unpredictable macro factors compared to a standard 10% rate for broader tech/consumer equities.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">2.5%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Mining is a depleting asset business, but major players like FCX continually replace reserves. A 2.5% terminal growth rate anchors long-term growth slightly below global GDP, reflecting inflation pricing power offset by the sheer difficulty of endless volume expansion.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ FCF PROJECTIONS TABLE ═══ -->
