  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>

  <h3>Upside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Copper Supercycle:</strong> If AI data centers and grid modernizations accelerate faster than anticipated, a structural deficit could drive copper prices well beyond historical norms, vastly expanding margins.</li>
    <li><strong>Grasberg Extensions:</strong> Further successful underground transitions or new discoveries at their crown jewel mine in Indonesia could extend the life of mine and boost volume.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Commodity Price Crashes:</strong> A global recession could crush copper demand in the short term, leading to negative FCF and necessitating debt issuance.</li>
    <li><strong>Geopolitical/Nationalization Risks:</strong> A significant portion of operations are in Indonesia (Grasberg). Changes in tax regimes, export bans, or forced divestitures are constant threats.</li>
    <li><strong>Environmental and CapEx Blowouts:</strong> Mining is prone to operational disasters or severe cost overruns on new projects, which destroy shareholder value quickly.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a higher discount rate (11%) for FCX?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Mining companies face extreme cyclicality, high capital intensity, and significant geopolitical/environmental risks. An 11% WACC demands a higher return to compensate investors for taking on these outsized operational and macro risks compared to a broad index fund.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is Free Cash Flow so much lower than Operating Cash Flow?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Mining requires massive, constant reinvestment just to maintain current production levels (Maintenance CapEx), plus huge investments to develop new ore bodies (Growth CapEx). This capital intensity drags down FCF compared to OCF.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, tax situation, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

